\begin_layout Subsection*

\lang english
c)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
let 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 and define:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
I=\mathbb{N}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{i}=\left(-1,\frac{1}{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
\begin_inset Formula $\forall i\in I$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an open set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
let's examine the intersection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
first it is trivial that every point 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\left(-1,0\right)$
\end_inset

 belongs to the intersection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
secondly, 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 also belongs to the intersection because:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall i\in I:-1\leq0\leq\frac{1}{i}\longrightarrow0\in\bigcap_{i\in I}A_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
in addition, any point larger than 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 doesn't belong to the intersection because:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall\epsilon>0,\exists i=\left\lceil \frac{1}{\epsilon}\right\rceil \in I:\epsilon\notin A_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 is a boundary point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
hence:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bigcap_{i\in I}A_{i}=\left(-1,0\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
and of course this is not an open set, because it contains a boundary point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\lang english
note: we could generalized this example to any 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 by padding the vector with zeros.
\end_layout

